  "messages": [
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "contents": [
        {
          "$type": "text",
          "text": "{\"workouts\":[{\"day_of_week\":2,\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"title\":\"Easy Aerobic Run\",\"target_distance_km\":4,\"target_duration_minutes\":30,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":450,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":450,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":480,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Walk briskly for 2 minutes, then settle into a very easy jog. No pressure on pace here.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":20,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":450,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Run at a conversational pace. You should be able to speak in full sentences without gasping. Stay in the 7:00-8:00 per km range from your Daniels-Gilbert zones.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":480,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Ease back to a walk. Let your heart rate come down gradually.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"Start with a 2-minute brisk walk, then ease into your slowest comfortable jog pace.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Walk for 2 to 3 minutes after the run. Gentle calf and hip flexor stretches while your legs are warm.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"This is your foundational aerobic run. The goal is time on feet, not speed. Your Daniels-Gilbert easy zone sits at 7:00-8:00 per km. Stay toward the slower end if anything feels hard. At 15 km per week with no race history, building aerobic base is the entire job right now. Running slowly is not a limitation. It is the method.\",\"perceived_effort\":4},{\"day_of_week\":4,\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"title\":\"Short Easy Run with Strides\",\"target_distance_km\":3,\"target_duration_minutes\":25,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":450,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":390,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":480,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Easy walk to jog transition. Keep it relaxed.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":12,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":450,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Steady easy running in your Daniels-Gilbert easy zone, 7:00-8:00 per km. Conversational effort throughout.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":4,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":390,\"intensity\":\"Moderate\",\"repetitions\":4,\"notes\":\"4 x 20-second gentle accelerations. Not a sprint. Think smooth and light-footed. Walk or jog easy for 40 seconds between each one. These teach your legs to turn over faster without stressing your aerobic system.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":4,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":480,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Walk it out. Shake out your legs gently.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"Walk for 2 minutes, then jog very easily into the run. No sudden pace changes early on.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"2 to 3 minutes of easy walking. Focus on relaxed breathing before stretching.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"The strides at the end of this run introduce a small neuromuscular stimulus. They are short enough that they do not add meaningful stress to your aerobic system. What they do is remind your legs what faster turnover feels like. This matters for a 5K goal because race pace will be faster than your daily easy pace. Keep total volume modest. You are still early in base-building.\",\"perceived_effort\":4},{\"day_of_week\":6,\"workout_type\":\"LongRun\",\"title\":\"Long Run\",\"target_distance_km\":6,\"target_duration_minutes\":45,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":480,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":480,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":510,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Start slower than you think you need to. The first few minutes should feel almost too easy.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":35,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":480,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Settle into a steady easy effort. Use the slower end of your Daniels-Gilbert easy zone, around 7:45-8:00 per km. Your only job is to finish feeling like you could have kept going.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":510,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Slow to a walk for the final few minutes. Do not stop abruptly.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"Begin with a 3-minute walk. Your long run starts slower than your midweek runs, not faster.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Walk for 3 to 5 minutes. Focus on hip flexors, hamstrings, and calves while muscles are warm. Hydrate.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"The long run builds your aerobic ceiling. At 6 km it is only 1 km above your current longest run, which keeps the progression safe and within the 10% weekly volume guideline. Stay at the slower end of your Daniels-Gilbert easy zone throughout. There is no benefit to going faster on this run. Fatigue accumulates faster than fitness when you push the long run. Time on feet is the whole point.\",\"perceived_effort\":5}]}"
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
